{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χᾰραδρ-ιός</b>, ὁ, <br /> a <b>bird,</b> probably the <b>thickknee</b> or <b>Norfolk plover, Charadrius oedicnemus,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 266, 1141, 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ τῶν ἐντὸς παθῶν” 37, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 593b15, 615a1, LXX.Lev.11.19, LXX.Deu.14.17(18) \">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]; it was very greedy, hence proverbial χαραδριοῦ βίον ζῆν, of a glutton, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 494b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; the sight of it was held to be a cure for the jaundice,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare 6th c.BC: Hipponax Iambographus 52, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.681c, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 17.13. \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G9699","accentedUnicode":"χαραδριός","shortDef":"a curlew","mediumDef":"a curlew","stepGloss":"a curlew","stepTransliteration":"charadrios","_step_Type":"word"}]}